1. Cultus is the greater comfort and the higher standard oi living that civilized prosperity brings, humanitas is the feeling, quickened by enlightenment and wider human intercourse, of the bond between man and man as beings of one race. Both, by soften· ing the savage instincta, diminish the manifestation of that crude kind oi physical courage which warlike people understand by the word “ bravery.”

2,3. minime . . . saepecommeant. Caesar meansthat the Belgicus have less trade with civilized natione than the other inhabitants oi Gaul have; the words saepe commeant belong closely together as an expression denoting the frequent coming and going oi the tradere, and minime modifies this combined expression.

10. ln the manuscripts of Caesar’s writings, as they have come down to us, there is an addition to this chapter which there is strong reason to believe Caesar never wrote. As the passage is regularly printed in editions oi Caesar, it seems best to give it here, although undesirable to inflict it upon the reader iu the body oi the text. Itis as follows :-

Eorum unapars, quam Gallos obtinere dictum est, initium capit a flumine Rhodano, continetur Garumna flumine, Oceano, finibus Belgarum, attingit etiam ab Sequanis et Helvetiis flumen Rhenum, vergit ad septentriones. Belgae ab extremis Galliae finibus ori- untur, pertinent ad inferiorem partem fluminis Rheni, spectant in septentrionem et orientem solem.
